content:
Declarative calculation procedures are a key component of the ratings engine. Along with calculation matrices, they are the main components of any rating engine. They take an input JSON and run through a series of matrix lookups and calculations to calculate ratings for policy products.

A well-formed calculation procedure contains constants, variables, and calculation steps, including:

* Calculations
* Matrix lookups
* Aggregation steps (optional)

Calculation procedures can take a single input, a single set of inputs, or multiple arrays of inputs. They run through all their steps once for a single input or single array of inputs and return a calculation or array of calculations.

Aggregation steps in calculation procedures put together the results of each run through themselves, perform operations on them, then output the results of the operations.

Beginning with the Summer '19 release, declarative calculation procedures support grouped calculation matrices and row-versioned calculation matrices.

Calculation procedures can be used to calculate coverage premiums, insured party premiums, insured item premiums, and insurance policy premiums. They can also calculate attribute-based prices for products.

Preprocessor and postprocessor classes can be used if you need to massage your input data or output data before and after it's processed by a calculation procedure.
title: Understanding Declarative Calculation Procedures in OmniStudio
